ents <i>ans</i> ‘god’ + <i>ger</i> ‘spear’ (Old Norse <i>geirr</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Johannes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]},{"name":"Dukas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Greek.  See  <b>Luke</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Luke","meanings":["Middle English vernacular form of   Lucas  , Latin form of the post-classical Greek name <i>Loukas</i> ‘man from Lucania’. This owes its perennial popularity throughout Christian Europe to the fact that, from the 2nd century onwards, the third gospel in the New Testament has been ascribed to the Lucas or Luke mentioned at various places in Acts and in the Epistles. Little is known about him beyond the facts that he was a doctor, a Gentile, and a friend and convert of St Paul. The name was borne by the character  Luke Skywalker  in the film Star Wars (  1977 ), and rose sharply in popularity in the 1990s."]}]},{"name":"ANGELOS","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Marian name honouring <i>Nuestra Señora de los Ángeles</i> ‘Our Lady of the Angels’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Doukas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Spyros, Anastasios, Aphrodite, Apostolos, Athanasios, Constantine, Costas, Dimitrios, Kalliopi, Kimon, Panagiotis.","Greek: from medieval Greek <i>doukas</i> ‘duke, lord’, from Latin <i>dux</i>. This was the name of a family of imperial rank in medieval Byzantium."],"variants":[{"name":"Dukas","meanings":["Greek.  See  <b>Luke</b> ."]}]},{"name":"ANGELOS","type":"FIRST","attribu